Die Verlierer bleiben Herausforderer
HARARE: Vor den Präsidentschaftswahlen in diesem Monat war ich überzeugt davon, dass Unregelmäßigkeiten bei den Wahlen ernsthafte Konsequenzen in Simbabwe selbst und im ganzen südlichen Afrika hätten.
Trotz der Schatten von Krieg und Terrorismus rief ich zu fairen und freien Wahlen auf.
Die Menschen von Simbabwe haben sie nicht bekommen.
Stattdessen haben sie Terror erhalten.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe and the Zimbabwe African National Union – Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terror is attributed to the criminals among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men all supported by the police.
Owing to the succession of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas.
Moreover, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and Chitungwiza.
Given there were not enough polling stations, in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, more than 360,000 people stood in line without being able to cast their ballot in the urn.
I still question the legality of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented our party observers from being present at 52% of rural polling stations.
Near the end of voting, our party observers were absent from 6 out of 10 polling stations in rural areas.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were only controlled by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes went to Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential election, in which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million cast votes.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the Zimbabwean people and is seen as illegitimate by them.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied the right to freely and democratically elect their president.
The fight over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation exceeds 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to have this acknowledged.
Maybe it's not too late for that yet.
I write this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand as a faithful servant to the people and go the distance with them.
Perhaps the government wants to arrest me.
I was also arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government can never break the will of the people to assert their rights and power.
It lies in our hands to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not let despair overcome us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his thugs are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to stay strong and finish what we have begun together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who would not be driven away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very steep path together to bring about a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people has rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve kindness and enthusiasm.
I notice that the people of Zimbabwe are impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for a political process to occur, they must be patient and wait.
The people cannot simply accept these elections, but they must not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want the change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that corruption during elections is widespread across Africa.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deception at the polls seem to be the norm.
There is always some kind of crisis in Africa due to elections.
Alas, the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it comes time to give the people their right to vote.
But those who want something different can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
Noch ist Zeit, aus unserer Erfahrung die Lehren für Afrika und die Welt zu ziehen.
Mein Volk ist in der Stunde seiner größten Not.
Ich gelobe, es nicht zu verlassen.
